Class ArraySet<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractSet<E>
        • ArraySet<E>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.Set<E>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Domain

    public class ArraySet<E>
extends java.util.AbstractSet<E>
    A Set implementation backed by an ArrayList. This is good for more or less immutable sets, but isn't part of standard Java.

      • ArraySet

        public ArraySet(java.util.Collection<? extends E> c)
        Construct and return a new ArraySet containing the elements of the given collection and with capacity as needed to whole them all. Per the contract of the Set interface in the Collections Framework, duplicate elements (according to equals()) are not added mulitple times.
